        Two hours into Territory Two, I am already cataloging the differences.

        The ground has gone soft underfoot—not quite mud but yielding, spongy, like walking on carpet over padding. My boots leave shallow impressions that fill with water seconds after I lift my feet. The forest canopy has opened up, replaced by wide sky and scattered trees—everything brighter and wetter and more colorful than Territory One's green-brown shadows.

        And the guides are _completely_ different.

        Streamwalker moves ahead with flowing grace, their vines undulating in smooth waves, and there is no sound except the soft whisper of vegetation—calm, serene, almost meditative.

        Brightbloom bounces alongside me like an enthusiastic orange cloud.

        Brightbloom says, "Oh, the wetlands are wonderful! So much water, everything's alive—you can feel it in the soil—do you feel it? The energy? It's everywhere!"

        Scout bounces in response, apparently finding a kindred spirit in Brightbloom's enthusiasm.

        I smile despite my lingering sadness about Leafwhisper and Rootwalker.

        I say, "It's definitely wetter."

        Brightbloom says, "Much wetter! Territory One is lovely, but all those big trees drink so much that the ground gets dry between root systems—here there's water in the air, water in the ground, water in every plant. We're all swimming really, just slowly!"

        I say, quietly, "Buddy, are we actually swimming?"

        Buddy says, "No, Kira. You are walking on saturated soil. However, I am detecting elevated humidity levels. Staying hydrated remains important even in moist environments…"

        I say, "Thanks, Buddy."

        Streamwalker says, "River ahead, quarter kilometer—we'll cross before evening."

        Their voice is so different from Leafwhisper's rapid cascade of information or Rootwalker's grounded syllables. Streamwalker sounds like water itself—flowing and patient.

        The terrain shifts as we walk. More standing water appears—small pools reflecting sky, channels cutting between plant clusters. The vegetation changes too: tall reeds, broad-leafed water plants, flowers in purples and yellows and that same bright orange as Brightbloom's blooms.

        Brightbloom explains, "Everything here is adapted for moisture. See those tall ones? They filter water through their roots—very efficient, part of the territory's purification network. And those floating clusters? They actually move locations based on nutrient availability—very mobile, excellent problem-solvers!"

        I feel a pang. Leafwhisper would have loved this—would have launched into twenty minutes of explanation about water-based plant networks and adaptive root structures…

        I take a breath. Leafwhisper is back in Territory One. That is okay. That is how this works.

        I say, "The purple flowers are beautiful."
      </text>
